text:
this is the symbol for survivor 
i relate to this in ways 
that on some days 
i dont even want to face the day 
or get out of bed
because of the sights 
you put in my head 
because of you 
i was terrified 
to go outside 
and see the sunrise 
but for some reason i never said no 
which doesn't mean yes
but for you it seemed apparent 
that my unsaid answer was a go ahead 
well it wasn't you fool 
but it wasn't okay 
not any of the days
but from that i learned
so many things 
i learned to say no 
and go away 
and from overcoming
the terrible circumstances 
i am alive today
and i'm not afraid

text:
rami malek opened up about the sexual assault claims surrounding bryan singer, who directed him in bohemian rhapsody.
. 
in a conversation at the santa barbara international film festival where he was honored for his portrayal of queen frontman freddie mercury, malek was asked about the recent allegations against the filmmaker. â€œmy heart goes out to anyone who has to live through anything like what iâ€™ve heard and what is out there,â€ malek told the audience. â€œitâ€™s awful, itâ€™s remarkable that this happens, i can appreciate so much what theyâ€™ve been through and how difficult this must be for them. in the light of the #metoo era that this somehow seems to exist after that, itâ€™s a horrible thing.â€ malek said he found talking about his own experiences with the accused director to be difficult because he wanted the focus to be on the film and queen, but didnâ€™t â€œwant anyone to not feel like they can share their story.â€ â€œiâ€™ve sat here and talked about how everyone deserves a voice and anyone who wants to talk about what happened with bryan deserves to have their voice heard,â€ malek told the crowd. â€œin my situation with bryan, it was not pleasant, not at all. and thatâ€™s about what i can say about it at this point.â€ malek reiterated that singer had been fired from the film. the director, however, had been removed from the production for asking to delay working on the film, and not for the abuse claims.

in january, singer was accused of having sex with four men who claim they were underage in an investigative feature on the atlantic. those werenâ€™t the first claims to surface against singer: he was accused of rape in december 2017 by cesar sanchez-guzman, who was 17 at the time of the alleged incident.

text:
when it comes to sexual shame, we cannot rid or remove the shame we are holding... however, we can play with it...we can make art with it, and allow it to evolve into a practice of embodiment; learning exactly how we feel on the inside, instead of reliving the old tale in our heads. 
this type of trauma requires us to explore ways that protect and make us feel safe in our own skin. taking time to notice our body state and working in ways to connect and communicate. hopefully giving us a better recognition of what it is, we truly need from our partners to trust and feel out of harms way. .
.
.
â›“ @remishibari .
.

with that being said, too many philanthropic organizations cater to a white washed version of fun and do not consider other groups of people when planning these events. it's important that if you want to unify people for a greater cause that you use your resources to involve as many demographics as you can. .

thrilled for this early reader copy of why we lie by the inimitable @amyimpellizzeri 
coming march 5, 2019! pre-order now! ğŸ“š
why we lie examines the unexpected consequences of those who tell the truth about abuse and those who lie, and asks the question: is the truth always worth the cost?
authored by former biglaw litigator, two-year d.c. federal court clerk, amy impellizzeri's why we lie exposes the core of the #metoo movement in the legal/political realm--where powerful men have long been given a pass on criminal behavior, and victims have been discounted even within their closest circles.
ğŸ“š
rising star politician and lawyer, jude birch, is clearly keeping secrets about his past from his wife. jude has been the bystander of a seemingly gang-related shooting, but as the secrets kept since law school unravel--with the help of a zealous news reporter and the capitol police--his wife realizes he might not have been an unintended victim after all. meanwhile, she makes every effort to clamp down a past marked by abuse and lies, and even a false accusation that still haunts her.
.
.
.
.

text:
kids waiting patiently in the wings to perform their very modern zombie dance. their class wowed the audience with a very spooky, very unusual dance. 
another class of older students had all eyes on them while performing a mix of dance and martial arts with the only girl in the performance playing a harassed victim of boys teasing and bullying her. by the end of the dance she had successfully stopped her attackers and remained the only one standing while the perpetrators lay on the floor around her. with more than a nod to "eve teasing", the school showed just how progressive it can be by reminding girls they have power over harassment they often face.

text:
i think we all need reminders of positives, so this is mine right now for you:

i hope you remember always that you don't deserve to be hurt,  not ever--not even by yourself.

you do deserve to be treated with compassion, empathy, and love by others and by yourself.

i hope you take good care of yourself. and i hope you keep connecting with others. we need those connections. and we need to treat ourselves gently and kindly, as kindly and gently as we would a friend.

love to you all,
cheryl rainfield, author of scars, stained, hunted

p. s. if it helps you, feel free to download this video and play it whenever you need to. i mean every word.

i've uploaded it to youtube, too, in case that makes it easier for you to bookmark or download.

text:
someone wrote this to me. i got this from my email on this morning. this individual read my article on my brother being falsely accused of sexual assault and molestation at the age of 13. in my brotherâ€™s case, the individual who accused him was my stepmother against her than 9 year old daughter, whom admitted years later that nothing ever took place and my brother never touched her. she also stated that her mother,â€made me say it.
this individual who wrote me understood and could relate to my article, as i am certain far too many can relate but the way the system is designed, they do not really care if there is no evidence, especially for that of the life of a black man or youth who is being accused. often times our own for selfish reasons will destroy a life out of their own self issues, which is the case for my brother whom still to this day is effected and countless other lives behind a lie created by others with no repercussions. this is another form of social injustice and we must change the narrative on this as well. we cannot continue to allow such and the individual making false accusations and charges just be allowed to walk away scot free and go on in life while the lie of such has destroyed a life. #falselyaccusedhelp #falselyaccused #falselyaccusedsomeoneofrape #changethenarrativekp #changethenarrative #voicesup #voiceofthepeople #voiceofthecommunity #bridgingthegap #urbancreativity #stopbullying #blackbypopulardemand #wedemandjustice #changestartswithin #rapeculture #metoo #stopliesaboutrape #rapeisnotajoke

text:
another christina lauren novel, also finished in the #24in48 for you guys today.  dating you hating you was an absolute riot to read. when two hollywood agents meet and sparks fly, they kind of test the waters in a romantic fling.  however, this comes to a halt when their agencies merge and both are suddenly competing for the same job.  the book's description starts with: "all's fair in love and war." if you've been following me for any length of time, you will find that i love strong, feminist ladies.  i love females who do their thing and don't let others stop them. this book addresses misogyny in the work place and it's such a needed issue to be discussed.  in the time of #metoo reading books that address these issues are necessary and important.  kudos to christina lauren for handling this topic and making me cheer so hard to the protagonist in her endeavors!

california. atÂ the time of his murder in june 2018, he was also awaiting trial for a 2016 domestic-abuse case, in which he was charged with aggravated battery of a pregnant woman, domestic battery by strangulation, false imprisonment, and witness tampering. taking in the full scope of these events is difficult and overwhelming, so weâ€™ve compiled a timeline to try to make sense of the situation.

pre-2014

text: youth mentor and sexual assault interventionist.  this is the last role i ever imagined i'd have. i was a wild child.  i wont tell young people what to do. i want to help them find their voice and self love. i want them to honor intuition.  i may tell a few warning stories but mostly just want to create a space where they feel safe to share and call me if they get in a pickle. god knows i know my way out of a pickle.  i want them to understand what healthy dating choices look like. i'm a very lucky lady i hope these teens are just as lucky. what kind of teenager were you? who did you look up to? who made it easy to be honest?  #mentor #youth #teens #teenager #datingviolence #guidance #mistakes #giveback #payitforward #safehouse #powerandcontrolwheel #sexualassault #domesticviolence #metoo #youthfulmistakes #survivor  #support #supportsystem #wisdom #wildchild #dontmesswithmygirls #gotyourbacklittleone #womensempowerment #whoruntheworld #girlpower

text: 21 years ago  i failed at taking my own life. 21 years ago i should have gotten the help i needed. i fell through the cracks and continued my life in a blur. becoming a parent 9 years ago made me see a lot of ugly parts of myself that were not easy to except. the way i reacted towards my son was not okay. i thought to myself, â€˜ if love my son then why do i act this way?â€™. 21 years after my failed suicide attempt i finally came to terms with the dark parts of myself. i learned that these behaviors were because of multiple traumas as a child & as an adult. i didnâ€™t think i could continue on as a parent if iâ€™m perfectly honest. i thought, â€˜ iâ€™m fucked up so iâ€™m going to fuck my son up.â€™ i honestly had no where & no one to turn to. i felt very alone in my illness but i knew deep down my son deserved better. so i started to read about trauma & the effects it had on my brain. i started reading about triggers & how to deal with them. knowledge is power. and even though my mind thinks differently than most people it doesnâ€™t make it wrong. itâ€™s just who i am. 21 years later, at 40, iâ€™m okay with who i am. and for the first time in 9 years i think i might be an okay parent. i just hope & pray that jude will be a happy, well adjusted man one day. and that he loves himself always. much love to all of you. be kind to yourself; your story isnâ€™t over yet. the best is yet to come â¤ï¸ #parenthood #mentalhealth #cptsd #projectsemicolon #suicideprevention #singleparent #selflove #knowledgeispower #metoo #recovery

esta pelÃ­cula toma como temÃ¡tica principal los certÃ¡menes de belleza, los

la trama es simple, no se hace complicaciones al momento de presentar sus escenas, se

pantalla. tiene un estilo similar a #sierraburgerssisaloser, pero menos romÃ¡ntico. aquÃ­ la protagonista no lidia con un amor imposible, sino con la bÃºsqueda de un lugar en el mundo y el significado de su existir. uno de los puntos mÃ¡s resaltantes es que no se trata de un pesado drama lleno de lÃ¡grimas, sino de un metraje reflexivo y motivacional que deja una bonita enseÃ±anza al final de todo.

no es una novedad que se toquen estos temas, hay muchÃ­simas series y producciones cinematogrÃ¡ficas que tratan sobre la aceptaciÃ³n corporal, no obstante "dumplin" logra manejar correctamente estos tÃ³picos de forma directa y sin pretensiones gracias al gran optimismo que refleja su narrativa. text:
wow.  you guys, i talked about my journey to a large group of people for the first time thursday.  at my workplace.  the audience included the man i love, colleagues, and former and current students.  i felt as if i stood there naked. .
immediately after i was unsure whether or not i had done the right thing.  like when you tear a band-aid off and realize that it hurt like heck, but it's too late.  i found it impossible to read the audience response.  i couldn't tell if they were extremely uncomfortable, in complete disbelief, or deep in reflection. .
i was so tired afterward and i woke up the next morning feeling hungover, like i had been drunk the night before and done something really stupid.  i still feel kind of raw and definitely exposed and like i want to run far away. i wonder if adam and eve felt like this when they realized they were naked... .
i won't run away, but that instinct is sure there.  i know that i have an imperative to share my story.  it sure is easier to do it from behind a keyboard than in a room full of people. â¤ï¸
.
#livingoutloud #livingmybiggestlife #heartwork #hardwork #healthjourney #fearisaliar #metoo

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
according to the times, cambridge analytica bought the data from aleksandr kogan, a russian-american academic. kogan, who told facebook he was conducting academic research, built a facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." when users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytica until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

text:
i'm these guys!! i had no homecoming date either, just hugged the wall.

never felt like i belonged or one of the cool, popular kids.

the all american guy: tall, dark, handsome or blonde hair, blue eye jock or whatever that cliche saying is what people want.

i didn't fit those categories in school. i did have friends that are labeled as nerds but hey these people have feelings!

this is why i am a voice for my daughter monica who has autism, what society calls different!

i know what's it's like to be left out. 
under my watch i choose to educate, stand up for my people's, include them to experience things everyone else does!

p.s. if you have ever felt judged, left out for looking or being different, comment these words: me too below: ğŸ‘‡

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
andy warhol said - â€œin the future everybody will be famous for 15 minutesâ€ 
and thank fuck for that. 
fame (and elitism) only works on the concept that it is scarce and that it is â€œspecialâ€ and that the people that have it are somehow better than you. so we tuck and starve and shame and dedicate ourselves to this falsity. 
to isolate or seperate yourself from your sameness, connection and similarity to other humans is the first cause of illness. it causes fear and anxiety and loneliness - whether u are the one isolating - or the one being isolated. (look at racism for example - i mean really! what a ridiculous fucking concept that was ... donâ€™t even get me started on religion! )
the people that make diamond rings know that if they arenâ€™t seen as â€œrareâ€ they will lose their value in society ( when we all know they are just compressed shiny coal) 
now the â€œeliteâ€ might not want to give up their power - but you certainly donâ€™t have to believe that you are lacking in yours! ğŸ¤©â¤ï¸â­ï¸ğŸ’¥
things like instagram and social media (used correctly)  help pull down and tear apart this disconnect - as does yoga, music, art, nature, reading, sharing, family, singing, loving, laughing, lifting each other up, supporting small business, sharing posts on things we believe in, meditation, drinking cups of tea, making time for each other, slowing down and valuing each other. the rich, the poor the old, the fat, the skinny, the ugly, the sick, the happy, the famous, the hermits, the extroverts and the introverts....
deep down we are all coal and diamonds - and even if we forget sometimes - we can never ever ever be disconnected from each other or the true source of life - â¤ï¸ğŸ™
itâ€™s impossible

text:
â€œexposedâ€
archival pigment print, vintage x-ray box, steel, plexiglass 
with â€œritual castingsâ€ and â€œthe panty projectâ€ 
the wash (as it seams) solo exhibition @msuunionartgallery
january 21 - march 2, 2019
artist lecture february 26, 2019
.
the panty project is an ongoing social practice project. participants, womxn and those who identify as womxn, courageously share with me their stories of experienced gendered transgressions and violent aggressions, whether cultural and/or interpersonal. participants write a word or phrase onto the panel of their selected undergarment; i hand-embroider over their mark-making and photograph them as if they have been taken off. this work addresses the inherent misogyny within our language, and the consequential "essestializing" of womxn, which reduces womxn, and those who identify as womxn, to "less than." this work is about healing and transcendence. 
womxn's long-silenced voices must be heard.
.

text:
feminists don't wear pink (and other lies) amazing women on what the f-word means to them by scarlett curtis
.
.
description:
.
in an age of constant controversy over womenâ€™s issues, including the #metoo movement and the likes of trump and kavanaugh scandals, it is with perfect timing that a new collection of stories on feminism is welcomed into the publishing world.

curated by scarlett curtis, a journalist and activist, feminists donâ€™t wear pink (and other lies) brings together 52 women to talk about exactly what the â€˜f-wordâ€™ means to them. these amazing women include: authors such as dolly alderton (everything i know about love) and helen fielding (bridget jonesâ€™s diary); actresses including saoirse ronan, emma watson, and keira knightly; youtubers zoe sugg and tanya burr; and a whole host of other empowering female figures with a story to tell.

not only does it contain a plethora of recognisable names from all different fields, the royalties from every sale of the book go to girl up, a global leadership development initiative that strives for gender equality and achieve a world where every girl has the same opportunity as the next person, regardless of race, religion, ethnicity, sexuality, age or ability.

the book is split into different sections, with five main elements detailing the pathway to understanding feminism â€“ epiphany, anger, joy, action, and education. there is also a â€˜poetry breakâ€™ halfway through, full-page quotes, suggestions of further reading from emma watson (â€˜our shared shelfâ€™) and, finally, a few lined pages at the back to jot down any notes you have while reading or inspiring quotes you want to remember.
this book combines everything you need to know about feminism in one handy volume that you can dip in and out of at your leisure. it isnâ€™t there to judge you for not knowing as much about feminism as you feel like you should, or to overwhelm you with so much knowledge on the vast topic that you have to try and wade through to get some sort of understanding from it.
it also hopes to (and arguably successful in its quest to) eliminate the common misconceptions of the term. curtis herself says that she used to think she didnâ€™t want to be

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
were you alone for valentines day?

i used to feel like that at one point in life. then i realised something. 
a relationship will fail 99% of the time because people stop looking after the seed you plant within the first few months. "what seed james?" the seed that gets planted when you first lay eyes on each other. the little sprout that emerges when you first hold hands. the leaves that bloom when you have the first kiss. 
months into this magical experience we put a glass ball around our little tree. we deprive it of the nutrients it needs.

we start to feel complacent and stop making effort. we feel like we own our other half. 
shatter the glass around that little tree...
let it breathe, nurture it and allow it to flourish once more.

realise you will never own anybody and you can only bring someone into your life when you are fully whole in yourself.

here's a news flash.

you have been and always will be whole.

if you felt alone yesterday do not worry. the time is coming and it will come into your life when you are ready. work harder on yourself until then.

follow @jamesmalins

text:
lucky to have a mother who wakes me up (litterally) for the important things, the last morning in aus i danced on the beach at sunrise. we were hundreds of womxn dressed in red for v-day (valentines day co-opted to vagina day by local and global movements) as we remembered those femmes that have been killed at the hands of a patriarchal and racist society and celebrated those who are still standing. through the singing and speaches the rain bucketed down drenching us all a much needed water for the parched summer, mixing with the tears of many. 
im grateful that this is being remembered and celebrated, that this is uplifting and exciting for me... now lets let our celebration flow over to communities in need. lets put our money where our mouth is.

below is a link to an organisation that supports criminalised women and girls, and their children, both inside and outside prison in australia. a large percentage of this population is indigenous. 
https://sistersinside.com.au/about/support-us/

#byehomebye #blackhistorymonth #vday #metoo #onebillionrising #capitalflow #sistersinside #weareonaboriginalland

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnnâ€™s don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analyticaâ€™s parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from koganâ€™s app may not have been completely deleted. koganâ€™s app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
i feel like i always look better in pictures than i do in person ğŸ˜… i think we all suffer with body dysmorphia to some degree, especially if you suffer from conditions like anxiety and depression like me. we all have internal struggles that everyone else is blind to but it consumes our lives. these past few months have been so hard, and staying consistent with my goals has become increasingly difficult, in and out of the gym. i know most of you know me as the strong one or the tough one. most of you aren't aware of my internal struggles because i don't make them know. just know you can be strong while dealing with mental illness ğŸ’ªğŸ¼ i believe in you all, because i believe in me. if i can overcome what ails me, y'all can too! ğŸ¤— there's an unhealthy stigma of just hiding our mental health, people will be a lot more understanding if they just open up to one another even just a little bit.

on that note, i still think i look good ğŸ˜ however, there's always room for improvement! i love lifting weights because it's so empowering. not only as a woman, but as a human being in general. i know i can't control what goes on inside of my body, but i definitely can control the outside. i can change my environment and change my habits to live the healthiest life i can. i love going to work and being around people who keep it real and fun at the same time. ğŸ˜„ i am so grateful for the people around me, especially those who go out of their way to check up on me! thank you guys so much! ğŸ’š

text:
the buzz of the lights. that is all you can hear in this big #gymnasium, the buzz of the lights overhead and the sound of #brenda tracyâ€™s voice, which remains steady even as she begins to cry.

her gaze shifts to the floor, if only for a moment. standing alone on an empty #basketball court, she straightens up and looks at the hundreds of people watching from the stands.

dressed in a black t-shirt and jeans, tracy resumes telling them about the night so long ago when she stopped by a friendâ€™s apartment. she recalls the #football #players who were there, how they persuaded her to have a drink, how she passed out a short time later. â€œthe first time i regained #consciousness, i became immediately aware i was laying on my back on the floor,â€ she says. â€œi was #naked and i couldnâ€™t move my arms or legs.â€ the man on her left tried to force her to have oral #sex. so did the man on her right. â€œso i turned from them and looked up and the third man was #raping me,â€ she says. â€œand i remember feeling like i was trying to say or yell â€˜stop.â€™â€ twenty years later, this is what the 45-year-old mother of two does, traveling the country to stand before strangers and share her most awful memory. she has appeared before 110,000 fans at #michiganâ€™s football #stadium and 15 or so players on a basketball team. this crusade, which started years before the #metoo movement, takes her any place where people will listen.

on this night, at sacramento state, the #school has made attendance #mandatory for all of its athletes. a half-hour earlier, the 500 or so young men and #women walked in chatting, laughing, searching for friends to sit beside; now they have fallen quiet, leaning forward, some of them lowering their heads.

tracy has no memorized speech, no notes or litany of #statistics about #sexualviolence in #america. she hits her #audience with something different: sheer honesty, a graphic and unflinching #description of that night.

text:
according to the times, cambridge analytica bought the data from aleksandr kogan, a russian-american academic. kogan, who told facebook he was conducting academic research, built a facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." when users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytica until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

text:
eight days to #oscars ğŸ¬

this year, two movies about #british queens are up for oscars (unless you also count #bohemianrhapsody which admittedly is about a british #queen as well). mary queen of scots didn't live up to the initial promise and ended up with two nominations. the favourite, however, has gained major momentum. 
it started off as a critical hit that was written off as too artsy to really be in contention. gradually, it has reached dark horse status. the film now has a serious shot at an upset in coveted categories such as picture and supporting actress.
it helps the movie's case that it's so sharply in tune with the #metoo era, and that it has three of the greatest thespians of our generation chewing the scenery like nobody's business. this one fires on all cylinders.

this year, two movies about #british queens are up for oscars (unless you also count #bohemianrhapsody which admittedly is about a british #queen as well). mary queen of scots didn't live up to the initial promise and ended up with two nominations. the favourite, however, has gained major momentum. 
it started off as a critical hit that was written off as too artsy to really be in contention. gradually, it has reached dark horse status. the film now has a serious shot at an upset in coveted categories such as picture and supporting actress.
it helps the movie's case that it is so sharply in tune with the #metoo era, and that it has three of the greatest thespians of our generation chewing the scenery like nobody's business. this one fires on all cylinders.

throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaignâ€™s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there â€œcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheatingâ€. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesdayâ€™s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text:
an ode to liberated women -  @sketchesartofficial 
liberation is different for every woman and it is only upto her what she defines as liberation in her journey. here we show a journey that starts from a past rooted in pain: a kind of pain that gives one depth, and moves towards healing: here there are breaths to be taken and a lesson to be recalled. lesson that height is just as important as depth to create balance and height cannot be reached without tending to the wounds that the depth brought with it. finally, the ladder to liberation: giving your emotions the worth they deserve, growing out of the societal expectations, choosing to not let yourself be defined by anyone or anything else other than yourself, and eventually rising above own self image as well to open your inner eyes to see how limitless you are. we chose a girl to reflect this journey of rising above because we believe it starts with her. she represents & educates the family, leads the community to health, and will eventually walk the world towards healing with her sensitivity as her strength and vulnerability as her armor.

#thesketches #anodetoliberatedwomen #metoo

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

an ode to liberated women -  @sketchesartofficial 
liberation is different for every woman and it is only upto her what she defines as liberation in her journey. here we show a journey that starts from a past rooted in pain: a kind of pain that gives one depth, and moves towards healing: here there are breaths to be taken and a lesson to be recalled. lesson that height is just as important as depth to create balance and height cannot be reached without tending to the wounds that the depth brought with it. finally, the ladder to liberation: giving your emotions the worth they deserve, growing out of the societal expectations, choosing to not let yourself be defined by anyone or anything else other than yourself, and eventually rising above own self image as well to open your inner eyes to see how limitless you are. we chose a girl to reflect this journey of rising above because we believe it starts with her. she represents & educates the family, leads the community to health, and will eventually walk the world towards healing with her sensitivity as her strength and vulnerability as her armor.

#thesketches #anodetoliberatedwomen #metoo

text:
there's not a single woman nominated for director this year.

the organization has diversified its ranks in terms of race and gender, but when it comes to its biggest awards â€” best picture, directing, screenplay â€” it's still a boys' club.

remember the year of the woman? of course you don't, because there've been so many, not just in hollywood but in the country at large. each time a year is labeled one of change for females, it disappears into the miasma of memory because the change was never real.
the first yow came in 1992, when an unprecedented number of women were elected to the senate after the anita hill/clarence thomas hearings, prompting sen. barbara mikulski to scoff: "calling 1992 the year of the woman makes it sound like the year of the caribou or the year of the asparagus." oscar made yow its theme the following year, opening the show with a photo of 67 female winners and declaring, "oscar celebrates women and the movies." hollywood followed with several more yows â€” indeed, in the mid-1990s every year seemed like a yow thanks to three studios being run by women (sherry lansing, amy pascal and stacey snider). the most recent yow came in 2018 with the double whammy of the #metoo and time's up movements, fueling hope that perhaps â€” possibly, maybe â€” hollywood would never need another yow. if only that were true. certainly in the executive suites women have moved forward in leaps and bounds. but further down, change has been slow, as evident in the current oscar race.

academy president john bailey noted at the feb. 4 nominees lunch that more women have beenÂ nominatedÂ this year than ever before: 59 of the 212 nominees for the 91st oscars are female, up from 51 last year. true, there's a panoply of women filling less prominent categories such as live-action, documentary and animated shorts. but dig deeper and women are as rare in other categories as female members of the augusta national.

text:
i have friends on twitter, like at sweetsoulkisses and at luv_n_adventure who helped support me through my first #nanowrimo on â€œa hard run into hellâ€ book 4, the true story of my dad and i trying to save my mom from stage 3 cancer, the very same year my mom died.
i have friends like at sheplaysloud, who is the reason there even is a cookbook in the making. not only did she give me the suggestion for it but she gifted me the title as well, â€œsometimes i bakeâ€.
i have friends like at fairycemetery who gives me a safe space to share without judgement and also makes me laugh so hard itâ€™s like iâ€™ve just done 250 sit ups. or at apocketsaint who read an early chapter of â€œtwitter: stories from the underbellyâ€ book and gave feedback, has read a few of my wattpad projects, and gave feedback on my first feeble attempts at audio readings of my own poetry. lol
i have friends like at crimson_snark who has probably read more of my works on wattpad than anyone else i know. she also helped with some early chapters of â€œtwitter: stories from the underbellyâ€. i have the 26 beautiful people from twitter who went through my twitter book questionnaire to share their experiences and thoughts. or the 65 wonderful twitter people who allowed me to use their quotes in the book.
i have people like the courageous 7 sexual assault survivors who came forward to share their stories and thoughts by going through my not-so-fun #sexualassault questionnaire. i have the 49 amazing sexual assault survivors on twitter who kindly gave me permission to use their quotes in the #metoo #whywomendontreport #whyididntreport #notokay chapters.
i have more people than i will probably ever know of who showed up for me. and i hope iâ€™ve turned that around to support and encourage others as well.
i dunno. i donâ€™t have the normal life or normal friends i can meet for tea. but i am fortunate that i have a posse all over the world, thanks to social media, who step forward with their support of me and my writing. and thereâ€™s nothing more special and phenomenal than people like that.

text:
@ronwyden that townhall made me lose every bit of respect i had for you. i have been working with your office for a year and things have gotten worse. you don't hold those that violate federal law accountable and you clearly don't respect or want to hear minority stories told by our own voice. clearly you want to keep oregon white and only use minority and veteran stories as anecdotes and to pull at heart strings but you will be damned if we tell our own stories.  i am disgusted by that farce and your inability to hold a school that dictates to the va what they will and won't do and that is heavily funded by the va but everyone is too afraid to say anything to them. i was hoping tonight i  would find out you are more than talk sadly that is all you are.

.

.

text:
there is no "perfect victim" or "perfect reaction" to sexual assault. it often seems that no matter what i do, it is not the right thing. some people tell me that i just need to move on with my life, others say i am not "healed" because i keep "dwelling on what happened." people have told me to stop calling myself a victim and start calling myself a survivor. people have told me that i need to stop being so angry and that forgiveness is what will set me free. i am tired of being told by people who didn't experience what happened to me telling me how to respond. you have a right to your emotions and reactions.

comment below â¬‡ï¸ how have you coped with unsolicited "advice" and victim blaming?

text:
tonight i did cardio in order to stop running.
_________________________________________________ as contradictory as that sounds, hear me out. tonight, i got myself to the gym and did over a hour of cardio. i did that, even though my mind was urging me to escape reality through sleeping or drinking. 
now, that may not seem like much. but to me, that's a massive victory. i worked out to prove that i was no longer controlled by the past. i ran for over 60 minutes in order to stop running from my past. i'm through being stuck in the vicious cycles from past toxic encounters. i'm not going to hide behind alcohol, sleep, or silence anymore. 
i ran today in order to stop running from my past. i ran to find my voice and raise it against those individuals who have hurt and/or violated me 
yes, i am an activist for the therapeutic effects of physical activity haha. .
.
.

text:
how #metoo is battling gender-based violence
#
the #metoo movement swept india last year when the bollywood actress tanushree dutta accused actor and filmmaker nana patekar of sexually harassing her in 2008 on the set for the film horn ok pleassss. in october last year, she also filed a first information report (fir) against him and others with police. it has been reported that patekar has denied the allegations and issued a legal notice to her to withdraw the allegations. dutta was also in the news more recently, putting a â€œcurseâ€ on film choreographer ganesh acharya, actor rakhi sawant and producer sami siddiqui for what she suggested was enabling the alleged abuse.these allegations made by such a well-known figure changed the course of the #metoo movement in india and opened the floodgates for many other women working in bollywood, the media, corporations and government to allege sexual harassment by high-profile and powerful men. social media platforms were flooded with #metoo stories and outrage, highlighting what has always been a taboo subject in india: the extent of harassment and violence against women, along with the deep-rooted injustice and inequality they face.the #metoo campaign has provided a gateway for indian women to vocalise the â€œenough is enoughâ€ message andâ€¦
link: https://metoozoo.com/news/how-metoo-is-battling-gender-based-violence/

this is 2019 amy. she knew the only way out was to go through it, so she did. my god, did she go through it! it was much harder than she expected it to be, but turning back wasnâ€™t an option so she pushed through. when she came stumbling out the other side she wasnâ€™t met with immediate joy like she had anticipated. she felt sad, confused, isolated, wronged, and angry, but becoming bitter wasnâ€™t an option either so she pushed through. 
____
she spoke her truth, she allowed herself to fall apart, she leaned on her tribe to help her stand back up again, and she put all of her faith in god to lead her down the path of the life she was meant to live. 
___
2018 did not define her, but the emotional distress that comes from having the courage to speak up only to be met with disbelief because the perpetrator denied it and the only witness within ear shot chose to protect himself over doing the right thing, stays with a person for a very long time. 
___
her story is still unfolding, but every day she wakes up with a grateful heart for a fresh start where she gets to decide who to surround herself with and a deeper understanding that the energy she puts out into the universe is the energy she will get back. and you better believe it has been one of fierce determination for whole-hearted connections! 
____
this is 2019 amy. sheâ€™s as imperfect as she was the year before but her voice is louder and she stands tall with her shoulders back and her tits out. sheâ€™s going to be the best version of herself yet. she sees you and she wants that for you too, so sheâ€™s here for you if you need her. donâ€™t be scared to reach out.

text:
**long post**
when i was 18, a classmate at nec raped me. i didnâ€™t report it because just a few months prior, my friend reported and instead got in trouble for underage drinking and the rapist was not punished. i didnâ€™t tell anybody except my closest friends, and i truly believed that it was somehow my fault, even though it was 200% the fault of the person who decided it was okay to treat another human being that way. i remember waking up in rage at 3 am, sobbing to close friends, because it was too much to process. even now, 6 years later, thinking about it makes my heart race and i break out in cold sweat. 
i wish that the nec community was more receptive to talking about this. i wish the school did not punish victims, but instead proactively protected their students. so @necmusic, i call to you to make better choices in the future, and take this seriously. your students come with hopes and dreams, and fostering musicians is not just about the performance. 
huge shoutout to @fishyinthesie for all the advocacy she has been doing, and for inspiring me to speak up about something iâ€™ve hidden for 6 years. you are so brave for doing what you do and speaking up on behalf of all the nec students. â¤ï¸
